Excited to Introduce the Elì B. Release 01- Denim Collection. 

This first collection pays homage to the great, Patrick Kelly (and the denim he wore to wrap each show) Patrick was a celebrated African American designer who came to fame in France. Kelly was born and raised in Mississippi by his mother and his grandmother. His uninhibited vision resulted in Kelly becoming the first American and first Black designer to be voted into the Chambre Syndicale du Prêt-à-Porter des Couturiers et des Créateurs de Mode, a French association for ready-to-wear designers. Kelly's designs were noted for their exuberance, and references to pop culture and Black folklore. 

Though Black fashion designers have consistently pushed the industry’s barriers, expanding sartorial paradigms through diverse and critically engaged practices, Patrick Kelly was undoubtedly a true pioneer. 

Elì B honors every designer that made room for us to express ourselves through fabrics, in hopes to make people feel. 

Discover the collection now, at  elìb.com

For Ashi:
The post I never wanted to write. You left us on the 23rd and it’s not that I can’t find the words, it’s that there are too many. And all of them would be true, but none would adequate.

After nearly 17 glorious years, I don’t know how to function without you. This grief is fierce. You were by my side every step of the way. My ride-or-die, my compass, and most importantly, my familiar. I’m proud to say you knew nothing but love and that we fulfilled our promise to you. Thank you for choosing me — you crazy, perfect creature.

My wife and I reached a mental tipping point this week — a need to slow the F down and reassess what brings us joy and name the choices that induce self-inflicted suffering.

So I sat down to read from these two glorious humans, and found a message echoing in both. 

From @induaroraofficial’s YOGA:

“For information, you can go to Google. For knowledge, you can go to conferences/workshops/texts. For wisdom, we have to come back to ourselves. Solid, real answers come only from within. If it comes through anyone/anything else, it becomes dependency.”

From @eliseloehnen’s ON OUR BEST BEHAVIOR (releasing 5/23):

“We have been led to believe that something primal and essential, our relationship to the universal force — God, nature, true self, whatever you want to call it — must be forced through the prism of an interpreter. And so we go there for approval, rather than trusting in ourselves.”

Interpret as you will, but I’m off to be with myself in practice and meditation. Thank you Indu and Elise. ❤️

Ragnar would like to remind you that asana can be a physical expression of concept: like the fact that y’all means ALL (the name of tomorrow’s @thehausofphoenix class). I’ll guide you through a front-body opening practice to embrace the LARGENESS of y’all. The definition will be specific to your experience: celebrating Pride as a LGBTQ+ member, a chosen family member, or as an accomplice or ally, and remembering that the opposite of curiosity is judgement. So (be curious!) if you find yourself angered/triggered/judgemental, try flipping it (like into Upward Facing Bow, our peak pose) and feel your world expand. Happy #pridemonth y’all — to all.

Many moons ago, I first shared the concept of ‘aim true’ with my students @kripalucenter. I can’t put my finger on it, but something about Kripalu inspired me: I knew it was fertile ground for exploring this important concept that launched me into a whirlwind of creation and growth.

And here I am on this Healing Retreat, a decade later, knowing I’ve returned home. Back to myself — back on these grounds, having aimed true in ways I never would have imagined. My arrow launched beyond my mat into a world urging me to embrace my voice, truth, and queerness. And now I’m here, surrounded by chosen family: moving and dancing in queer-friendly spaces with my femme-sister @mynameisjessamyn, absorbing the wisdom of yoga as a student, exploring vulnerability in our queer share circle, and savouring every last bite from one of my favorite kitchens in the world.

Thank you to @kripalucenter and @them for reminding this “friend of Dorothy” that there’s no place like home. 

Read more about our experience in my bio link. #KripaluPartner

Do you love teaching or experiencing new and creative ways to strengthen and celebrate your body? If your hand shot up, come join our Block Party Program over @thehausofphoenix ! It’s made up of four 45 minute fusion classes inspired by yoga, Pilates, strength training, and cardio. Bonus: it’s wicked fun and 20% off during the month of July for all Haus of Phoenix subscribers! 😎 AND it’s all yours for six months. Link in bio to join in on the fun!

PS: This is my home practice version of the first week (45 minutes smooshed into 45 seconds!) called Welcome to the Block Party.

A solid chunk of my childhood was spent with my face behind a GameBoy. I was particularly ravenous for Tetris, still seeing the falling blocks on the inside of my eyelids after I’d close my eyes to sleep. So, when my friend Lauren invited us over for dinner to enjoy her fruit ‘Tetris’ salad, my 8-year-old self yelped with glee. As if eating wasn’t enough fun already! Filled with inspiration, I pulled on summer bounty: juicy tomatoes, perfect peaches, crunchy cucumbers, and delectable watermelon. Bolster that with some classic Greek Salad components, and voila! A feast for your eyes, stomach, and inner child.

In a world of oversharing, it’s simultaneously thrilling and frustrating to hide a major part of yourself. I thrive on the lack of the needing the world’s approval, yet also hunger to be seen for who I know I already am.

That’s why this might be my favorite photo of myself. I took it in 2021 after writing a particularly fulfilling scene in my novel. Because I am an author. Yes — I’ve published books, but what people dont know, is I’m actually a novelist. Not “will be a novelist” — we put too much weight on external success (like getting published), but rather “I am a novelist”. I sat down and did the damn thing. I wrote (and heavily edited) a novel. I’m writing another. I’m even starting to publish books myself through Inky Phoenix Press. When will mine be published? Who knows, but that doesn’t change who I know I am.

All this to say, check out my latest Haus Blog: Welcome to The Inky Phoenix (link in bio) where I share a glimmer of this experience and how it continues to shape me. @theinkyphoenix

Be careful not to lose your humanity.

—
Be careful to separate people from the policies of their governments. 
Be careful to separate people from the actions of terrorists who live among them.

Be careful not to collapse history and context into narrow interpretation.
Be careful not to eschew complexity and nuance for the sake of memeification. 

Be careful to recognize that grief for one side does not mean hate for the other.
Be careful to understand that support for one side does not mean hate for the other.

Be careful of gaslighting on a mass level: disinformation and denial of loss. 
Be careful not to dismiss the excruciating and real pain of others. Do not make it worse.

Be careful not to say things online that you would not say to someone in real life.
Be careful not to add hatred on top of hatred; we are all being crushed underneath its compounding weight.

Be careful not to lose empathy for those with whom you disagree.
Be careful not to dehumanize others. Doing so dehumanizes you. 

Do not lose touch with the parts of you needed most: 
Your compassion. Your humanity. Your care.

If you search “gratitude” on the online thesaurus, you’ll find these top four descriptors: acknowledgment, obligation, recognition, then finally, the classic “thanks”.

I initially found “obligation” curious. It isn’t seamless. For example, “I have so much obligation for my wife” — probably not the best sentence to deliver with flowers. But if you inspect the meaning, alongside its thesaurus friends, it’s actually genius. How can we experience true gratitude without the obligation to recognize what we’re thankful for and actively acknowledge it? I have been “practicing gratitudes” by noting what stories I’ve built that stand between me and feeling grateful for what I have. By recognizing how lucky I am, and verbalizing each special moment, feeling, person. It’s my daily obligation to myself and those in my orbit.

This book started it all for me. Okay, maybe didn’t *start* as I was 21 when it published, but as you can see from the well-worn cover of this original copy, it TRANSFORMED me. I had already grown up believing in the power of magic and story. I was the kid who’d be happily locked away in a museum or left to my own devices for hours in the fantasy section of a bookstore. It wasn’t always seen as “mature” or fodder for success, but I refused to accept these elements of myself as childish. Then I stumbled upon AMERICAN GODS by @neilhimself : a masterpiece written by a respected literary god. Completely ahead of his time, he envisioned the clash between ancient and modern mythology, the brewing catastrophe between what we worship and what we’ve forgotten. He rooted a fantastical world in everyday life, and in doing so, he gave me permission to do the same. It’s how I think, write, and create. Simply put: it’s who I am.

I normally don’t pick titles of this magnitude for @theinkyphoenix because I like to amplify newer voices, but I am ecstatic to re-read this with the club and fall in love with it all over again. If you’re hankering for that kind of magic, you should join us. 

And if you already know AMERICAN GODS, then yes — this is my ode to Technical Boy.

These official moments feel surreal. I am a publisher. I get to shepherd stories into the world. And our first one is pure magic. I cannot wait to introduce everyone to STRANGE BEASTS by the genius @susanjmorris (second slide) published by @theinkyphoenix x @bindery_books 🖤

I’ve been dealing with shoulder tendonosis and mild cervical arthritis from an old whiplash injury for a while now. Add a partial supraspinatus tear since August and needless to say, my movement practice looks dramatically different. Modifications are now imperative, and patience is my daily teacher. It’s been a beast, but it’s also been a reminder of how lucky I am to move in this body, whatever that may look like. And remembering it will continue to change. All this to say: focus on what works and drop the lack mentality. 

If you’re looking for a range of supportive practices, you’ll find them in abundance @thehausofphoenix alongside myself, my Haus teachers, and regular guests.
